VII. The Lacedaemonians complain that The- mistocles is dragging out the time as long as pos- sible, and that the work is none the less going on. The chief authority is in the hands of the ephors. These send as ambassadors to Athens men who have held the highest offices. The Athenians have fenced in their gods with walls, the more easily to defend them from an enemy. This they have done in accordance with international law.

VIII. His fellow—citizens banished him by ostra- cism. When he was living at Argos, he was accused by the Lacedaemoniam, because, [as they said,] he had made an alliance with the Persian king for the conquest of Greece. Both Athenians and Lacedae- monians demanded his extradition, but he embarked on a ship and sailed to Ephesus.
